There's a few key observations to be made: 
(0) BST printed with Inorder traversal will yield a sorted sequence. 
(1) Find the middle of the sorted array --> that's the root
>> Hence everything to its left is the left subtree and everything to its right is the right subtree 
Note a side effect of this is the middle is always right biased making our lives easier because we just have to divide by 2. 

(2) Repeat until we finish going through the entire sorted array
>> How do we repeat? By recurring (use recursion) only on a subset of nums, as mentioned before everything to the left of the middle index is the left subtree [so you just defined you're subproblem there]
>> What does it mean to have gone through the entire sorted array? *When the nums we're passing is in empty*

 ```
TreeNode* sortedArrayToBST(vector<int>& nums) {
        // HEIGHT BALANCed!

        if (nums.size() == 0)
            return NULL;
        int mid = nums.size() / 2;
        TreeNode * newNode = new TreeNode(nums[mid]); // create a new node with the value of the middle of sorted array

        if (mid -1 >= 0){
            vector<int> left(nums.begin(), nums.begin() + mid);
            newNode->left = sortedArrayToBST(left); // to the left of this node is the sub-vector from 0 to mid (hence the end condition is when nums is empty)
        }

        if (mid + 1 < nums.size()){
            vector<int> right(nums.begin() + mid + 1, nums.end());
            newNode->right = sortedArrayToBST(right);
        }
        return newNode;
    }
