**Recursive Approach.**
**Binary Search and Divide & Conquer Technique used.**

**Note:- Divide the Problem into subparts, then solve the subparts and then get to the final solution.**

**Approach:-**

*    As the array is sorted, so the first technique that should come in our mind is **Binary Search**.
*   Then apply the Binary search by taking two pointers one is **left pointer(l)** at 0th index and **right pointer(r)** at last index.
*  Calculate mid and make the element present at that index as a root node.
*  Move the left side of Binary search tree. So update **r=mid-1** as all elements in left of Binary search tree are smaller then the root node.
*  Simillary do this for right side and now update **l=mid+1**.
*  After accessing all the elements return the node which is a Binary Search Tree.



class Solution {
public:

    TreeNode* fun(int start,int end,vector<int> &nums){
        if(start>end){                       //Base Condition
            return NULL;
        }

        int mid=start+(end-start)/2;         // mid value calculation for Binary search implementation
        TreeNode* node=new TreeNode(nums[mid]);        // creating the node
        node->left=fun(start,mid-1,nums);              // for left subtree
        node->right=fun(mid+1,end,nums);               // for right subtree
        return node;
    }

    TreeNode* sortedArrayToBST(vector<int>& nums) {
        int start=0;                   // left Pointer (l)
        int end=nums.size()-1;         // Right Pointer (r)
        TreeNode* root=fun(start,end,nums);
        return root;
    }
};

