# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Apply Somewhat same technique As applied in Binary Search

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
* From the given function we will call a new function which we will create.
* What we will do in our new function is that we will apply the same technique we apply in Binary Search.
* This technique is applied here because we are given an Array/Vector of sorted elements, so we can think that if we will make the mid as the root node, it will be easy to for a BST.
* As in a sorted array if we find the mid element , it is but obvious that all the elements on the left side of the mid element will be smaller and all the elements on the right side will be greater.
* So here to form the BST we will first find our Base condition, here the base condition will be if(s>e), i.e starting is greater than ending, it is same as if(s<=e) in Binary search. If the base condition is satisfied return NULL.
*  Now we will find mid.
* After finding the mid, create a new node with the value of mid, this node is the root node of our BST.
* Now for the left and right sub tree recursively call the new function with the change in parameters.
* For the left subtree starting will be same but ending will be mid-1.
* For the right subtree starting will be mid+1 ending will be same.


# Code
