# Intuition
In the beginning a trie might sound intimidating to implement and work with but if you understand it's basics, it's not as difficult as it looks. 

A trie is a tree-like data structure used to store a collection of strings or words. Each node in the Trie represents a character, and the path from the root node to a particular node represents a string or word. The end of a word is marked by a flag in the last node of the word.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d58fa8e4-92a2-48c0-aa61-ef031ae431e3_1679050425.241754.png)
In the above example we are storing:
```
["an", "ant", "car", "can", "cup"]
```
The root is an empty string. Starting from the root node, each subsequent level represents a character in the word being stored. For example, the first level has two nodes, each representing one of the two possible starting characters of the words being stored: 'a', and 'c'.
The end of a word is indicated by a special flag on the corresponding node. In this example, nodes for the end of "an", "ant", "car", "can" and "cup" have been marked as end nodes.

# Approach
Let's take an example of inserting one word into the Trie: "can"

Initialize the Trie with an empty root node.

#### Insert the word "can" into the Trie:

- Start at the root node.

- Insert the first character 'c' into the Trie. Check if the child node representing 'c' already exists. If it doesn't exist, create a new child node representing 'c'. Move the current node to the child node representing 'c'.

- Insert the second character 'a' into the Trie. Check if the child node representing 'a' already exists. If it doesn't exist, create a new child node representing 'a'. Move the current node to the child node representing 'a'.

- Insert the third character 'n' into the Trie. Check if the child node representing 'n' already exists. If it doesn't exist, create a new child node representing 'n'. Move the current node to the child node representing 'n'.

- Mark the last node as the end of the word "can".


#### Search for the word "can" in the Trie:

- Start at the root node.

- Follow the path for the characters 'c', 'a', and 'n' in the Trie. If any one character doesn't exist in the path, return false.

- Check if the last node is marked as the end of a word. Since it is, return true. The word "can" is in the Trie.


#### Search for the prefix "cab" in the Trie:

- Start at the root node.

- Follow the path for the characters 'c' and 'a' in the Trie. As the node with 'b' doesn't exist, return false.



# Code
```
struct TrieNode {
    bool end; // Flag to indicate whether this node represents the end of a word or not
    vector<TrieNode*>children=vector<TrieNode*>(26,nullptr); // Vector of pointers to child nodes for each possible character in the alphabet (26 lowercase English letters)
};

class Trie {
public:
    TrieNode* root;

    Trie() {
        root = new TrieNode();
    } 

    // Insert a word into the Trie
    void insert(string word) {
        TrieNode* start = this->root;
        for(int i=0; i<word.size(); ++i) {
            int index = word[i] - 'a';
            if(!start->children[index]) {
                start->children[index] = new TrieNode();
            }
            start = start->children[index];
        }
        start->end = true; // Mark the last node as the end of a word
    }

    // Search for a word in the Trie
    bool search(string word) {
        TrieNode* start = this->root;
        for(int i=0; i<word.size(); ++i) {
            int index = word[i] - 'a';
            if(!start->children[index]) {
                return false; // Word not found in the Trie
            }
            start = start->children[index];
        }
        return start->end; // Return true if the last node is marked as the end of a word
    }

    // Check if the Trie contains any word starting with the given prefix
    bool startsWith(string prefix) {
        TrieNode* start = this->root;
        for(int i=0; i<prefix.size(); i++) {
            int index = prefix[i] - 'a';
            if(!start->children[index]) {
                return false; // No word in the Trie starts with the given prefix
            }
            start = start->children[index];
        }
        return true; // At least one word in the Trie starts with the given prefix
    }
};

```

