solutions.content:
Okay, it looks like I have gained enough experience to mostly go in auto-pilot with trie-related problems: [Es ist noch kein Meister vom Himmel gefallen](https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/es_ist_noch_kein_Meister_von_Himmel_gefallen), indeed.

In this case I decided to split the logic into 2 parts:
* a struct `TrieNode` which would store all the data we need;
* the actual `Trie` class with the methods to perform the required tasks.

I did so in order to avoid unnecessary memory wastage: when we build our tree structure from each characer of each inserted string, no point in duplicating also every method.

Coming to `TrieNode`, all that we need in this struct are:
* `children`, an array of pointers to other `TrieNode` instances, with size set to 26, since the specs clearly mention only lowercase letters;
* `eow` which is a boolean flag to mark a node as matching the last character of a given word.

Going back to the `Trie` class, I declare a `TrieNode` `trie` element as a class variable and can then confidently skip declaring a constructor.

The `insert` method will just take the value of `trie`, assign it to `curr` and proceed to loop through each character in the provided string, normalise said character `c` to be in the necessary `0 - 25` range and then we have 2 options:
* `curr->children[c]` exists and thus it becomes our new `curr`;
* `curr->children[c]` does not exist, so we need to create one before making it our next `curr`.

Once we are done looping through the characters, we flag the `eow` property of the last node (the most recent value of `curr`) to be `true`.

`search` will follow a somehow specular logic, initialising `curr` with the value of `trie` and then looking for normalised each character `c` in the provided string, but when `curr->children[c]` is not found, we just return `false` (meaning we met a branch which has not been recorder - ie: no word matching that path was ever inserted); if we go out of the loop, we return the value of `returnResult || curr->eow`.

Now, you might have wondered why I added an extra parameter to `search` and defaulted it to `false` in this case.

Well, it was just to avoid code duplication, since `startsWith` does exactly all the same, but will always return `true` if we manage to exit the loop with all the characters provide, so all that this method needs to do is to run `search` with the provided word and the second variable set to `true` and we are done :)

The code:

```cpp
// separate struct, to save memory
struct TrieNode {
    TrieNode *children[26] = {NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL};
    bool eow = false;
};

class Trie {
    // private, because we are pros!
    TrieNode *trie = new TrieNode();
public:
    // constructor not really needed here

    void insert(string word) {
        TrieNode *curr = trie;
        for (char c: word) {
            // normalising c in the 0 - 25 range
            c -= 'a';
            // adding nodes as we need them
            if (!curr->children[c]) curr->children[c] = new TrieNode();
            // updating curr, deeper in the trie
            curr = curr->children[c];
        }
        // flagging the last node as the end of a word
        curr->eow = true;
    }

    bool search(string word, bool returnResult = false) {
        TrieNode *curr = trie;
        // search char by char
        for (char c: word) {
            c -= 'a';
            // at the first missing branch, we quit
            if (!curr->children[c]) return false;
            curr = curr->children[c];
        }
        // we return either returnResult or if the word was complete
        return returnResult || curr->eow;
    }

    bool startsWith(string prefix) {
        // just running a search, with a different variable
        return search(prefix, true);
    }
};
```

