# Approach

The solution uses an object `n` to represent the trie and a boolean $$isWord$$ to indicate if the current node is the end of a word.
The insert(word) method iterates through each character of the word, creating a new Trie object for the character if it doesn't exist and moving to the next node. At the end of the loop, the $$isWord$$ property of the last node is set to true.
The $$search(word)$$ method iterates through the characters of the word, returning false if a character is not found in the trie. It returns the $$isWord$$ property of the last node if the loop completes.
The startsWith(prefix) method is similar to the $$search(word)$$ method, but it returns true if the loop completes without returning false.

Overall, this implementation of Trie class in javascript is an elegant and efficient solution to the given problem as it uses object for representing trie and also uses recursion to search and check prefix, this makes code more readable and easy to understand.

